Housing/Real Estate Industry Data: August 2025 Release

Housing/Real Estate Industry Data: August 2025 ReleaseAug release of Jul data: Both used and new- build Greater Tokyo condo prices continued to rise, at \(175m (+28.4\% YoY)\) for new build and \(58.57m (+26.5\%)\) for used. In the central 23 yards, the gap narrowed at \(135.32m (+24.4\%)\) for new builds and \(14.7m (+38.7\%)\) for used.

Office vacancy rate in Tokyo's five central wards up 0.21ppt MoM to \(3.16\%\) . Rise in average asking rent continued at \(+4.4\%\) MoM to \(20,907 / \text{tsubo}\) Greater Tokyo condos put on sale up \(34.1\%\) to 2,006. Condos released for sale up in Tokyo and Saitama. Average price up \(28.4\%\) to \(100.75m\) Tokyo Kantei says price of used condos rose \(26.5\%\) to \(58.57m\) . The rise in average price continued but decelerated at \(+36.0\%\) at \(166.99m\) Monthly orders stayed weak at \(- 9.7\%\) YoY, but recovered on a seasonally adjusted annualized basis at \(712,000 (+9.9\% YoY)\) US new housing starts (SAAR basis) were \(- 0.6\%\) MoM to 652,000, with the median selling price \(- 5.8\%\) YoY and inventory \(+7.3\%\)

Share performance: In August, real estate stocks outperformed TOPIX. This was driven by a rebound from underperformance between May and July, fading rate hike expectations, and strong 1Q results (such as expanding office momentum and robust condo sales). Investors favored real estate stocks for their solid fundamentals and defensive earnings. A continued outperformance scenario assumes excess liquidity will keep attracting investment into defensively positioned real estate names. However, valuations have approached or exceeded April 2024 levels, when Mitsui Fudosan announced its long- term strategy and sector ratings rose. This raises the risk of a correction. Potential triggers include renewed rate hike expectations, a sharp rise in long- term interest rates globally, or renewed debate over restrictions on speculative condo transactions. The TSE REIT index slightly underperformed TOPIX in August but still ended in positive territory (Exhibit 9).

Overweight (O). The stock's total return is expected to exceed the average total return of the analyst's industry (or industry team's) coverage universe, on a risk-adjusted basis, over the next 12-18 months.

Equal-weight (E). The stock's total return is expected to be in line with the average total return of the analyst's industry (or industry team's) coverage universe, on a risk-adjusted basis, over the next 12-18 months.

Not-Rated (NR). Currently the analyst does not have adequate conviction about the stock's total return relative to the average total return of the analyst's industry (or industry team's) coverage universe, on a risk-adjusted basis, over the next 12-18 months.

Underweight (U). The stock's total return is expected to be below the average total return of the analyst's industry (or industry team's) coverage universe, on a risk-adjusted basis, over the next 12-18 months.
